Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
From: kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com (Kevin Brown)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: Mon, 23 Aug 1993 14:59:37 GMT

In article <25aeu1$eop@sol.cis.udel.edu> chavey@sol.cis.udel.edu (Laurent Chavey,,,sol.cis) writes:
>I just read the article about how linux users are #@##@.  I have worked 
>with ms window for now 3 years.  I have worked with a guy name Robert 
>Straus, that knows windows upside down, the internals and guts.  For my 
>part I am content to just be able to program some.  My unix experience is 
>the same.  I am not a god in anything, or else what am I doing here.  I 
>whish some people would show some humility and realise that Linux is a 
>non commercial product that allows people like me toplay arround with an 
>os, without having to spend 1000 of dollars.  

Not only that, but it'll allow you to do real work (word processing aside).

>On the other side ms window 
>is a commercial product, with which many people make a daily leaving and 
>for that reason, it is a product that responds to customer demands.  

I agree that many make a living with it, but I don't agree that Windoze
itself is a product that, through Microsoft, responds to customer demands.
Rather, other software vendors respond to customer demands by selling
software for it.

>For 
>the pc to have come so far, in s uch a short time, must mean that the pc 
>manufacturers are not totally stupid.  

That's right.  But the primary reason the PC has come such a long way is
that it is the only computer for which there are multiple manufacturers
competing with each other for the same basic hardware platform.  That's
why the prices are so low and *that's* why the PC is so popular.

>Even so window is a take out of 
>the box system, it was the intent of the designers, and it works.  

It installs, it works.  So does Linux.  But Windoze doesn't work *well*.
It's slow.  It crashes.  It wastes resources.

Linux works well.  It's fast.  It makes the most of the resources available.
It's damn near bulletproof.

Given the choice between the two, I'll use Linux except in cases where I
have to do something that *can't* be done on Linux but can be done under
Windoze, e.g. WYSIWYG word processing.

>Nt is a new technology, money is needed to develop it, and what gates 
>does so well is marketing.  unix is old, and has had a tendency to 
>refrain itself from the easy to install package.  

Linux and BSDI prove that Unix needn't be difficult to install.

>unlike ms window, unix 
>was intended for computer profesional, and that it does well.  but do not 
>forget that NT is for joe blow users, not people that have such a low 
>self esteem that they like to think of themselves as gods.  

I guess this remains to be seen.

>Now linux is also a great piece, if not a giant piece of software.  I 
>love it, and I have both window and linux on my machine.  I work with 
>both every day, and both provide me with services than one alone could 
>not.  

Could you describe what you do under Windoze and what you do under Linux?
It would provide an interesting example of the uses of each.


